     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"IR8A is an annual return of employee income that every Singapore employer must prepare for each employee who earned income during the calendar year. It summarises employment income, bonuses, CPF contributions, and any benefits-in-kind. Employers must submit it to IRAS and give a copy to each employee by 1 March each year."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"When is the IR8A submission deadline?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The deadline is 1 March each year for the preceding calendar year's income. For Year of Assessment 2026 (income earned in 2025), the deadline was 1 March 2026. For YA 2027 (income earned in 2026), the deadline is 1 March 2027. Late submission attracts a composition fine of up to S$1,000 per employee."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Who must submit IR8A in Singapore?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Every employer in Singapore must prepare IR8A for each employee who received employment income during the year, including part-time workers, casual workers, and directors. Employers with 5 or more employees must submit electronically via the Auto Inclusion Scheme. Employers with fewer than 5 employees can choose to submit manually or via AIS."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is the Auto Inclusion Scheme (AIS) for IR8A?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The Auto Inclusion Scheme (AIS) is an IRAS program where employers submit employee income data electronically. IRAS then pre-fills the employment income section of each employee's personal tax return automatically. Employers with 5 or more employees are required to participate. It removes the need for employees to manually enter their salary figures when filing personal tax."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What happens if I miss the IR8A deadline?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"IRAS can impose a composition fine of up to S$1,000 per employee for late or missing IR8A submissions. Repeated non-compliance can result in court proceedings. If you realise you have missed the deadline, submit as soon as possible and contact IRAS — voluntary disclosure before IRAS contacts you generally results in a lower penalty."}}
